```

The reason your links stay “highlighted” after you click them is that you’re styling both the `:hover` **and** the `:focus` states:

```css
.nav-link:hover,
.nav-link:focus {
  background: var(--light-nav-hover);
}
```

When you click a link (or button) it receives keyboard focus — and stays focused until something else takes focus — so your background rule for `:focus` keeps applying.

---

### Fix #1: CSS-only solution

1. **Remove** the `:focus` selector from your hover rule
2. If you still want to show a focus outline for keyboard users, switch to `:focus-visible` (supported in modern browsers)

```css
/* only show the hover background on mouse-over */
.nav-link:hover {
  background: var(--light-nav-hover);
}

/* suppress the “clicked” background */
.nav-link:focus {
  outline: none;             /* remove default outline if you like */
  background: none;          /* ensure no hover BG lingers */
}

/* optionally show a focus indicator for keyboard users */
.nav-link:focus-visible {
  outline: 2px solid var(--light-primary);
  /* you can even add a matching BG, if you prefer: */
  /* background: var(--light-nav-hover); */
}
```

Do the same in your mobile-menu rules:

```css
/* replace this... */
.mobile-menu .nav-link:hover,
.mobile-menu .nav-link:focus {
  background: var(--light-nav-hover);
}

/* ...with this */
.mobile-menu .nav-link:hover {
  background: var(--light-nav-hover);
}

.mobile-menu .nav-link:focus {
  outline: none;
  background: none;
}

.mobile-menu .nav-link:focus-visible {
  outline: 2px solid var(--light-primary);
}
```

---

### Fix #2: JavaScript blur-on-click

If you don’t care about keyboard focus styling at all, you can “immediately” blur the link/button on click so it never holds focus:

```js
document.querySelectorAll('.nav-link').forEach(el => {
  el.addEventListener('click', () => el.blur());
});
```

Place that at the bottom of your `<script>` block (after your existing listeners).  That way, as soon as the user clicks a link, it loses focus and the background goes away.

---

### Which to choose?

- **CSS-only** is more semantic and preserves keyboard accessibility (especially if you use `:focus-visible`).
- **JS blur-on-click** is a quick-and-dirty fix if you really don’t want any focus styling.

Either way, once you remove the `:focus` background rule (or immediately blur the element), the “sticky” highlight will be gone and you’ll only see your accent on actual hover.

