You’ve almost got it, but a couple of selector typos mean you’re still accidentally styling the wrong things. Let me walk through the two spots that need fixing:

---

### 1. Dark-mode nav-hover block

You have this:

```css
body.dark-mode .nav-link:hover,
body.dark-mode {
  background: var(--dark-nav-hover);
}
```

By listing `body.dark-mode` you’re giving your entire page a dark-nav-hover background! You only want the `.nav-link:hover` to pick up that color. Change it to:

```css
body.dark-mode .nav-link:hover {
  background: var(--dark-nav-hover);
}
```

---

### 2. Mobile-menu hover block

Similarly, you wrote:

```css
.mobile-menu .nav-link:hover,
.mobile-menu {
  background: var(--light-nav-hover);
}
```

That second selector means the entire `.mobile-menu` panel is getting the hover color. It should just be:

```css
.mobile-menu .nav-link:hover {
  background: var(--light-nav-hover);
}
```

---

### 3. Removing the lingering focus state

You still haven’t stripped out the `:focus` background rule. If you leave

```css
.nav-link:focus { /* or grouped with :hover */ 
  background: var(--light-nav-hover);
}
```

then clicks will keep the focus styling. You need to explicitly clear that:

```css
/* only highlight on hover */
.nav-link:hover {
  background: var(--light-nav-hover);
}

/* remove any background when it gains focus (e.g. after click) */
.nav-link:focus {
  outline: none;
  background: none;
}

/* if you want an accessible focus indicator for keyboard users */
.nav-link:focus-visible {
  outline: 2px solid var(--light-primary);
}
```

And do the same inside your mobile-menu rules:

```css
.mobile-menu .nav-link:hover {
  background: var(--light-nav-hover);
}
.mobile-menu .nav-link:focus {
  outline: none;
  background: none;
}
.mobile-menu .nav-link:focus-visible {
  outline: 2px solid var(--light-primary);
}
```

---

With those three fixes you’ll:

1. **Stop** accidentally coloring the whole page or menu container.
2. **Only** show the hover background while the mouse is over the link.
3. **Remove** the stuck “clicked” state by clearing the focus BG and (optionally) using `:focus-visible` for keyboard outlines.

You’re seeing the submenu stick open for the same reason your top-level menu stayed highlighted after a click: you’re using `:focus-within` to show the dropdown, and once you click a link inside the dropdown it gets focused, so the parent `<li>` always matches `:focus-within`, even when the mouse leaves.

You have two straightforward ways to fix it:

---

## 1) Pure-CSS approach: ditch `:focus-within` and only use `:hover`

Replace your

```css
/* this keeps it open if anything inside is focused */
.nav-item:focus-within .dropdown,
.nav-item:hover .dropdown {
  display: flex;
}
```

with

```css
/* only open on actual mouse-hover */
.nav-item:hover .dropdown {
  display: flex;
}
```

That way, as soon as the cursor leaves the `.nav-item`, the dropdown will disappear (CSS hover no longer applies).

> **⚠️ Downside:** keyboard users lose the ability to open the menu with Tab/Enter.

---

## 2) Hybrid CSS + JS (best of both worlds)

Keep keyboard accessibility, but switch from `:focus-within` to focusing only the **top-level** button, and auto-blur it when you click a submenu item.

### A) Tweak your CSS

```css
/* open on hover... */
.nav-item:hover .dropdown,
/* ...or when the top-level button itself is focused */
.nav-item .nav-link[aria-haspopup]:focus + .dropdown {
  display: flex;
}
```

Notice we removed `:focus-within` and replaced it with a **sibling** selector that only fires when the **button** is focused.  As soon as focus moves to one of the `<a>`s, the menu will close (focus is no longer on the button).

### B) Auto-blur the button after a submenu click

If you have submenu `<a>`s that don’t actually navigate away (e.g. `href="#"`), you’ll want to blur the button so that the dropdown doesn’t flicker open on hover or focus.  At the bottom of your `<script>`:

```js
// whenever a submenu link is clicked, remove focus from its parent button
document.querySelectorAll('.dropdown a').forEach(link => {
  link.addEventListener('click', () => {
    const btn = link.closest('.nav-item').querySelector('.nav-link[aria-haspopup]');
    if (btn) btn.blur();
  });
});
```

---

### Putting it all together

1. **CSS**

   ```css
   /* desktop dropdown: hover OR button-focus */
   .nav-item:hover .dropdown,
   .nav-item .nav-link[aria-haspopup]:focus + .dropdown {
     display: flex;
   }
   ```

2. **JS**

   ```js
   // blur the top-level button after a submenu click
   document.querySelectorAll('.dropdown a').forEach(link => {
     link.addEventListener('click', () => {
       const btn = link.closest('.nav-item').querySelector('.nav-link[aria-haspopup]');
       if (btn) btn.blur();
     });
   });
   ```

Now:

- **Mouse** — submenu opens on hover, closes on mouse-out.
- **Keyboard** — submenu opens when you Tab-focus the Services/Solutions button, but then closes as soon as you Tab into (or click) one of its links.
- No more “persistent” dropdown after a click.

It isn’t your JavaScript at all, it’s the way the header’s box model is calculated:

1. You’ve given the header a **`width: 100%`** _and_ `padding: 0 16px`.  
2. By default CSS uses the **content-box** model, so that padding is _added_ on top of the 100% and pushes you 32 px too wide → horizontal scrollbar.

---

## Two easy fixes

### A) Switch to `border-box`

```css
/* at the top of your stylesheet */
*,
*::before,
*::after {
  box-sizing: border-box;
}
```

With `border-box`, `width: 100%` **includes** your `padding: 0 16px`, so there’s never any overflow.

---

### B) Remove the explicit width

You don’t actually need `width: 100%` on a block‐level element:

```css
.header {
  /* remove width:100%; */
  /* keep your padding so the logo + controls stay inset */
  padding: 0 16px;
  position: sticky;
  top: 0;
  /* … everything else exactly the same … */
}
```

Without `width` it will naturally expand to fill its container **minus** the padding, so again—no scroll.

---

### (Optional) hide any residual scroll

If you want a belt-and-braces “no horizontal scroll anywhere” approach, you can add:

```css
html, body {
  overflow-x: hidden;
}
```

—but that can mask _other_ layout issues, so I’d start with A) or B) above.

---

### Summary

- **Preferred**: globally `box-sizing: border-box;`  
- **Alternatively**: drop the `width: 100%` on `.header`  
- No more accidental 32 px overshoot → no scrollbar → your sun/moon toggle always visible.

